<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910405-0097</DOCNO><DOCID>910405-0097.</DOCID><HL>   Hearings Are Slated   On Baby Bells' Role   In Information Services</HL><DATE>04/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   AIT BEL BLS NYN PAC SBC USW</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)TELEPHONE SYSTEMS, INCLUDING CELLULAR (TLS)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)COLORADO (CO)GEORGIA (GA)ILLINOIS (IL)MISSOURI (MO)NEW YORK (NY)PENNSYLVANIA (PA)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Federal Judge Harold Greene has orderedhearings April 18 and 19 on whether the seven regional Belltelephone companies should be allowed to providecomputer-based information services.   The Baby Bells currently are barred from theinformation-services business by the consent decree thatbroke up the Bell System in 1984. Judge Greene, who overseesthe consent decree, asked for opponents and proponents of therestriction to pick representatives to address 10 questions.Among other things, he asked about the status andeffectiveness of Federal Communications Commission and stateregulation of information services and what methods the Bellscould use to discriminate against competing informationproviders.</LP><TEXT>   The judge is reviewing the issue after the federal appealscourt here sent back his decision to bar the companies fromowning the contents of information services.</TEXT></DOC>